{
  "texts": [
    "Fortunately, theoretical energy losses associated with D 2 NN can be controlled by incorporating them into the optimization loss function, as depicted in Fig. 7g.",
    "Originally, the loss function is defined as the MSE between the inferred outputs E and the corresponding theoretical outputs Ê, which is f L ¼ 1",
    "It is worth noting that the original loss function inherently accounts for energy loss to some extent, yet the energy term constraints are not fully expressed during the training process.",
    "Instead, greater emphasis is placed on optimizing visibility.",
    "The introduction of a separate energy loss term aims to strike a balance of these two parameters."
  ]
}